Scott Goehring wrote:
>
>"Steve" == Steve Gardner <gardner@silas-2.cc.monash.edu.au> writes:
>
>Steve> For while
>Steve> it is true that there were serious uncertainties about how the
>Steve> Frankenstein Monster should be *interpreted* (because it didn't
>Steve> make any sense), there were no serious uncertainties as to what
>Steve> the Frankenstein Monster actually *said*, ie what it's text
>Steve> was, which is what you claim is the problem with
>Steve> other-modifying Rules.
>
>This is simply not true.  A myriad of "reported" changes to the
>Frankenstein Rule turned out to not have been made, because of error.
>Our handling of error in this situation was pathetic.  I believe that
>allowing self-modifying and other-modifying rules dramatically
>increases the possibility of an unchecked error cascade.  Aside from
>philosophical reasons, this is my primary opposition to them.

Hm, yes, now that I think back more carefully I think you're right about
the FM. But I still think that the argument from the case of the FM to
conclusions about self-modifying and other-modifying Rules *in general*
is a poor one. For the FM was a pretty atypical kind of case: a cluster
of Rules operating repeatedly to amend one of the cluster, and what is
more, doing so in a way such that the calculation of future amendments
depended critically on the results of past amendments. In other words, a
feedback loop. Given those particular and highly unusual circumstances,
any error that went undetected for any length of time was guaranteed in
that case to have cascading effects. This is, you are right to point
out, a recipe for disaster, and so it proved. But the fault in that case
was due to the particular way in which the FM worked (ie the feedback
loop); the Virus suffered from no such difficulties. So I don't think
you've established your case that the use of self- and other-modifying
Rules must of necessity dramatically increase the chances of an
unchecked error cascade. What you have established is that feedback
loops are to be avoided.


