Scott Goehring wrote:
>
>"Charles" == Charles E Carroll <ccarroll@nationwide.net> writes:
>
>Charles> No more than if there is a dispute over the effect of a
>Charles> Proposal, it seems to me.
>
>The problem is that we might not even know _IF_ a self-modifying or
>other-modifying rule has operated.  It's pretty obvious when a
>Proposal has been adopted.  The chance for error cascade is much
>greater when multiple major events (such as rule changes) can arise
>without any need for human action or even human awareness.

OK, but that's just a special case of the general argument for
Pragmatism. One doesn't say "At the beginning of the week, every Player
receives a VT from the Bank"; one says "As soon as possible after the
beginning of the week, the Chancellor shall pay out a VT to every
Player." In fact, the Virus was one of the earliest examples of the
application of Pragmatic principles to Rule-design. It didn't say "At
the beginning of the week, a random Rule is amended in such-and-such a
way."; it said "Once each week, the Rulekeepor selects a Rule at
random and amends it in such-and-such a way." And we never had any
problems with the Virus.

>>> The practical importance arises when you think about how you deal
>>> with error.  Our present Rules do not deal at all well with error
>>> with respect to the reporting of Proposal results, for example.
>
>Charles> Could you elaborate?
>
>Suppose the Assessor correctly reports that a Proposal has passed,
>then mistakenly reports that it did not pass, but the Assessor's
>mistake is not recognized for six months.  Under the present regime,
>the Rule Changes pursuant to that Proposal take effect at the time of
>the first report, even though nobody believed they were in effect for
>the subsequent six months.  This is unacceptable to me, and would not
>happen in the regime I propose.

Of course we all know that this is precisely what happened with the
adoption of Pragmatic Currencies. No-one could disagree that this
episode exposed a flaw in the system when dealing with errors in
announcing the results of Proposals. But the connection between this
episode and your argument against self-modifying and other-modifying
Rules escapes me.


