"Steve" == Steve Gardner <gardner@silas-2.cc.monash.edu.au> writes:

Steve> But the fault in that case was due to the particular way in
Steve> which the FM worked (ie the feedback loop); the Virus suffered
Steve> from no such difficulties.

Actually, I believe we have had cases where reported viral infections
turned out not to have happened because the Rulekeepor was mistaken as
to the number of Rules in the Ruleset.  Even if this actually never
happened, it was a possibility.

Steve> So I don't think you've established your case that the use of
Steve> self- and other-modifying Rules must of necessity dramatically
Steve> increase the chances of an unchecked error cascade. 

It is my opinion that every instance in which one might want to use a
self-modifying or other-modifying rule falls into one of three
categories:

1. sunset by self-repeal or temporary measure by self-amendment, which
   can be equally achieved without self-amendment using cut-on and
   cut-off dates;
2. modification upon proper player action, which can be achieved by
   directly authorizing the player to change the rules (making the
   change a player-caused rule change, something I have no problem
   with); and
3. unsafe automatic changes which either inherently lead to cascade
   errors, or at least prone to them.

Since the only desirable circumstances are (1) and (2), and both can
be achieved without using self-modifying Rules, I see no need for
them, and since prohibiting them protects from the undesirable
situations in (3), it is worth doing so.

